
================================================================================
                    ssX Supplemental License
                        ("The Hire the Team" Clause)
                            Version 1.0
                   Effective upon inclusion in any ssX distribution
================================================================================

This Supplemental License applies to all original contributions, modifications,
compatibility shims, build system infrastructure, and derived works authored by
ssX project contributors and incorporated into the ssX codebase ("Covered
Contributions"). It does not supersede the XFree86 License governing the
underlying source; it applies in addition to it.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
1. GRANT OF USE
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Permission is granted, free of charge, to any individual, non-profit
organization, educational institution, or open source project with annual
gross revenue not exceeding USD $1,000,000 to use, copy, modify, merge,
publish, distribute, and sublicense the Covered Contributions, subject to
the conditions of the underlying XFree86 License.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
2. DEFINITIONS
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

"Commercial Entity" means any corporation, LLC, partnership, or other
for-profit legal entity with annual gross revenue exceeding USD $1,000,000,
or any subsidiary, affiliate, successor, or acquiring entity thereof.
Revenue thresholds are evaluated at the parent entity level; subdivision
of a Commercial Entity into smaller legal entities for the purpose of
falling below the threshold constitutes a violation of Section 3.

"Project Contributors" means all individuals who have made commits, patches,
documentation, tooling, or other material contributions to the ssX codebase,
as recorded in the project's version control history. All Project Contributors
are considered equal co-authors of the Covered Contributions regardless of
contribution volume. A canonical list is maintained in CONTRIBUTORS at the
repository root; version control history is authoritative in the event of dispute.

"Covered Contributions" means all original work authored by any Project
Contributor and incorporated into the ssX codebase, including but not limited
to source code, build system definitions, compatibility shims, documentation,
and test infrastructure.

"Downstream Lockout" means any act by which a party receives the Covered
Contributions, modifies or builds upon them, and then restricts access to
the resulting source code through technical, legal, contractual, or
subscription-based mechanisms — including but not limited to paywall access,
CLA requirements, trademark enforcement, or binary-only distribution.

"Governance Capture" means any coordinated effort by a Commercial Entity to
acquire controlling influence over the ssX project's technical direction,
contributor base, or decision-making processes through employment of
contributors, funding dependencies, or organizational affiliation, without
satisfying the conditions of Section 4.

"Contribution Laundering" means the submission of contributions to the ssX
codebase by employees or agents of a Commercial Entity for the purpose of
establishing downstream usage rights, circumventing Section 3, or creating
the appearance of open source participation while the entity simultaneously
violates this license.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
3. COMMERCIAL USE RESTRICTION
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

A Commercial Entity may not, without a separate written commercial license
obtained under Section 4:

a) Deploy, distribute, or incorporate the Covered Contributions into any
   product or service offered for commercial gain;

b) Use the Covered Contributions in internal infrastructure, tooling, or
   pipelines that support revenue-generating activities;

c) Sublicense or relicense the Covered Contributions to a third party for
   commercial purposes;

d) Employ, contract, or retain any individual Project Contributor in a
   capacity that involves the Covered Contributions without simultaneously
   satisfying the conditions of Section 4 with respect to all Project
   Contributors — selective hiring to extract the project's value while
   leaving remaining contributors unpaid is explicitly prohibited;

e) Engage in Downstream Lockout with respect to any derivative of the
   Covered Contributions;

f) Engage in Governance Capture;

g) Engage in Contribution Laundering. Contributions submitted by employees
   or agents of a Commercial Entity in violation of this license do not
   grant that entity any usage rights and do not reduce that entity's
   obligations under this license;

h) Use trademark, patent, or trade secret claims to interfere with any
   Project Contributor's ability to develop, distribute, or enforce rights
   in the Covered Contributions;

i) Require any Project Contributor to sign a Contributor License Agreement
   (CLA), Imposed Monopoly Privileges mislabeled as IP, or similar instrument
   as a condition of accepting contributions, if doing so would transfer
   ownership or exclusive licensing rights to the Commercial Entity;

j) Distribute the Covered Contributions in binary form without simultaneously
   making the complete corresponding source available at no additional cost,
   under no additional legal restrictions, to all recipients.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
4. HOW TO OBTAIN A COMMERCIAL LICENSE
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

A commercial license is available. The negotiation process is as follows:

The Commercial Entity must extend a good-faith offer of full-time employment,
at market rate, to each and every Project Contributor listed in CONTRIBUTORS
at the time the entity first seeks to use the Covered Contributions commercially.

The following conditions apply to all such offers and, if accepted, to the
resulting employment relationship:

a) Compensation must be at or above prevailing market rate for the relevant
   role and jurisdiction, as determined by publicly available compensation surveys;

b) Source attribution for the Covered Contributions must be permanently
   retained in any derivative product or service, in both source and
   binary form;

c) No NDA, non-compete, Imposed Monopoly Privileges mislabeled as IP, or
   non-disparagement clause may be imposed that would in any way restrict
   any contributor's ability to continue contributing to ssX or any other
   open source project in their personal capacity;

d) No CLA or Imposed Monopoly Privileges mislabeled as IP transfer agreement
   may be required as a condition of continued contribution to ssX;

e) All offers must be extended simultaneously. Sequential offers designed
   to hire selectively while satisfying the letter of this clause constitute
   a violation of Section 3;

f) The employment offer may not be used as leverage to alter the governance,
   licensing, or technical direction of the ssX project;

g) Acceptance or rejection of an offer has no effect on the contributor's
   standing in the project or their rights under this license.

Acceptance of offers by all Project Contributors constitutes a perpetual,
royalty-free commercial license for the hiring entity. Rejection by any
individual contributor is that contributor's sole right and does not obligate
remaining contributors to accept or reject.

A Commercial Entity that extends good-faith simultaneous offers to all
Project Contributors and receives rejections from some may petition the
accepting contributors for a partial commercial license covering only those
contributors' individual Covered Contributions. Such a partial license
explicitly does not cover the Covered Contributions of non-accepting
contributors, and the Commercial Entity remains in violation of Section 3
if it uses those contributions without consent.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
5. CONTRIBUTOR AUTONOMY AND ANTI-CAPTURE
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

a) No Project Contributor may unilaterally grant a commercial license
   covering another contributor's work.

b) No external funding, sponsorship, or employment relationship may be used
   to obtain de facto control over the project's licensing or governance
   decisions. Any agreement between a Project Contributor and a Commercial
   Entity that purports to grant rights in other contributors' work is void
   with respect to those contributions.

c) No amendment to this license may be made under conditions of Governance
   Capture. Any amendment proposed while a Commercial Entity holds
   disproportionate influence over the contributor base — through employment
   of a majority of active contributors — is suspended pending resolution
   of that conflict of interest.

d) This clause may not be waived by any single contributor, including the
   project's founding members.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
6. PATENT NON-AGGRESSION
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

a) Any Commercial Entity that uses, distributes, or incorporates the Covered
   Contributions — whether under a valid commercial license or otherwise —
   automatically grants each Project Contributor a perpetual, worldwide,
   royalty-free, irrevocable license under any patent claims that entity
   controls which are necessarily infringed by the Covered Contributions.

b) Any Commercial Entity that initiates patent litigation against any Project
   Contributor alleging that the Covered Contributions infringe a patent —
   including cross-claims and counterclaims — forfeits any commercial license
   previously obtained under Section 4, immediately and without recourse,
   and becomes subject to the full restrictions of Section 3 retroactively
   from the date of first use.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
7. PAYWALL AND SUBSCRIPTION PROHIBITION
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Distribution of the Covered Contributions, or any derivative thereof, behind
a subscription paywall, access fee, or support contract as the primary means
of source access is prohibited. This provision targets the practice of
technical GPL compliance through source repositories accessible only to
paying customers. Any recipient of a binary distribution is entitled to
receive complete corresponding source under the same terms as this license,
at no additional cost.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
8. NO WARRANTY; NO SUPPORT
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

The Covered Contributions are provided "as is." Project Contributors are
under no obligation to provide support, maintenance, or compatibility
guarantees to any party operating outside the terms of Section 4.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
9. ENFORCEMENT
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Violation of Section 3 by a Commercial Entity constitutes copyright
infringement with respect to each Project Contributor whose work is
incorporated in the infringing use. Each Project Contributor retains
independent standing to enforce their rights under this license without
requiring the consent or participation of other contributors.

In any enforcement action brought under this license, the prevailing Project
Contributor(s) are entitled to recover reasonable attorney's fees and costs.
A Commercial Entity found to have engaged in Downstream Lockout, Governance
Capture, or Contribution Laundering as defined in Section 2 shall be liable
for enhanced damages reflecting the willful nature of the violation.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
10. SEVERABILITY
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

If any provision of this license is found unenforceable in a particular
jurisdiction, that provision shall be modified to the minimum extent
necessary to make it enforceable, and all other provisions shall remain
in full effect.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
11. AMENDMENTS
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

This license may be amended by consensus of the active Project Contributors
as recorded in the project's governance documentation, subject to the
anti-capture provisions of Section 5. Amendments are not retroactive; prior
versions of this license continue to govern Covered Contributions made
before the amendment date. The version number in the license header is
authoritative.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
12. SUPREMACY OF CONTRIBUTOR RIGHTS
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

In any conflict between the terms of this Supplemental License and any
agreement entered into by a Project Contributor with a third party — including
employment contracts, consulting agreements, or CLAs — this license governs
with respect to the Covered Contributions. No third-party agreement may
extinguish another contributor's rights under this license.

================================================================================
                HUMAN SOVEREIGNTY CLAUSE
                ("The AI-Assisted" Amendment)
                     Version 1.0
================================================================================

This amendment supplements the ssX Supplemental License and applies to
all contributions made after its effective date.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
1. DEFINITIONS
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

"AI-Assisted Contribution" means any contribution to the ssX codebase that
was created with the aid of an artificial intelligence, Large Language Model,
code generation tool, or similar computational assistant, where the human
contributor:

a) Made the primary architectural and design decisions;
b) Wrote or significantly refactored the core logic themselves;
c) Verified the code's correctness through testing and review;
d) Can defend every design decision in a code review.

"Generative AI Output" means code, documentation, or other content that was
primarily generated by an artificial intelligence system without significant
human structural modification, verification, or refactoring. This includes
but is not limited to:

a) Raw output from Large Language Models submitted without human editing
b) Code where the AI made the primary architectural decisions
c) Bulk-generated functions or modules without human design input
d) AI-generated content the contributor cannot defend in code review

"Augmented Coding" means the permitted use of AI tools as aids to enhance
human-authored work, including:

a) Spell-checking and grammar assistance
b) Suggesting alternative implementations (human evaluates and chooses)
c) Refactoring code the human contributor already wrote
d) Generating unit tests for human-authored code
e) Documentation assistance (outlines, grammar fixes)

"Structural Modification" means meaningful human intervention that changes
the fundamental design, logic flow, or architecture of AI-generated content,
including:

a) Adding comments explaining the "why" of functions (not just "what")
b) Modifying code paths based on human security analysis
c) Restructuring modules based on human architectural decisions
d) Replacing AI-suggested implementations with human-designed alternatives

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
2. HUMAN SOVEREIGNTY REQUIREMENT
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

All Project Contributors retain sovereign authorship over their contributions.
By submitting to ssX, each contributor affirms:

a) They are the primary author of the intellectual content they contribute;
b) They understand and can defend every line of code they submit;
c) They have made the architectural decisions, not merely accepted AI output;
d) They take sole responsibility for the logic, security, and correctness
   of their contributions.

Contributions that are primarily "Generative AI Output" without significant
human "Structural Modification" are violations of this license and may be
rejected at the maintainers' discretion.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
3. TRANSPARENCY DISCLOSURE
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

All contributors MUST disclose their tool usage in every commit message or
pull request description using the required format specified in CONTRIBUTING.md.

The following disclosure types are required:

a) "Tool-disclosure: None" - For pure human-authored work
b) "Tool-disclosure: AI used for [specific permitted use]"
   - For AI-Assisted Contributions (Augmented Coding)
c) DO NOT SUBMIT - For Generative AI Output without verification

Failure to include proper disclosure may result in rejection of the
contribution or revocation of commit authorship.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
4. PROHIBITED PRACTICES
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

The following practices are STRICTLY PROHIBITED:

a) Submitting raw Generative AI Output without human verification
b) Passing off AI-generated code as human-authored without disclosure
c) Using AI to "explain" code you did not write yourself
d) Submitting contributions where AI made primary architectural decisions
e) Bulk-generating code functions without human design input

Contributions in violation of this section do not grant the contributor
authorship rights and may be reverted.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
5. PERMITTED PRACTICES
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

The following practices are PERMITTED under "Augmented Coding":

a) Using AI for spell-checking and documentation grammar
b) Accepting AI suggestions for alternative implementations (human decides)
c) Using AI to refactor code the human contributor wrote
d) Using AI to generate unit tests for human-authored code
e) Using AI for finding typos in human-written code

In all cases, the human contributor must be the primary decision-maker
and take sole responsibility for the final contribution.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
6. ENFORCEMENT
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

a) Maintainers may reject contributions that appear to be Generative AI
   Output without significant Structural Modification

b) Repeated violations may result in contributor ban

c) Contributors found to have submitted Generative AI Output as their own
   work may have commits reverted

d) This clause supplements but does not replace the AI Training
   Prohibition in BLOCK_AI_TRAINING.md

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
7. INTERPRETATION
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

This Human Sovereignty Clause is designed to:

a) PERMIT AI-Assisted Contributions (human-driven, AI-aided)
b) PROHIBIT Generative AI Output passed off as human work
c) PROTECT the quality and integrity of the ssX codebase
d) PRESERVE human authorship and accountability

We welcome human contributors who use AI tools responsibly. We reject
attempts to substitute AI labor for human labor without disclosure.

*The human writes. The human decides. The human defends.*
*This is the ssX way.*

